According to the World Health Organization, there is a shortage of 100 million liters of blood in the world to meet the needs of the world's population.
In addition, the French Blood Establishment informs us that 90% of French people know that blood donation saves lives.
And despite this figure, only 4% make this gesture every year.
And this scenario is repeated in most industrialized countries.
Faced with this gap between human blood donations and the needs of the world's population, we must find an alternative to this practice, in order to respond to this real public health problem.
And, as surprising as it may seem, I may have found one of the solutions.
And the solution, I found it on a beach in Brittany.
Even as a child, I was fascinated by the oceans, and I think that Commander Cousteau's emissions were no stranger to them.
So I naturally decided to make it my job, and I became a doctor in marine biology.
An environment caught my attention very early on, because this environment was colonized by very ancient organisms.
This environment is the foreshore, or a scientific name for an environment that you must appreciate since in fact, it is the beach.
And the beach in Brittany is covered twice a day by the tide.
And the sand of this beach is home to very old organisms that you have certainly seen, by the traces that these organisms leave on the sand, by depositing your towel.
In fact, these traces testify to the presence of a marine organism called the arenicole.
So the arenicole is the name of a marine worm well known on the beaches in Brittany whose name in Breton is the Buzuc.
So I became interested in this marine worm to answer questions of respiratory ecophysiology.
So what does that mean?
Oh, it's simple, I was interested in the breathing of this marine worm.
I was actually trying to figure out how this worm breathed between high tide and low tide.
And in order to answer this fundamental research question, (Laughter) I became interested in the blood of this animal.
Indeed, blood is an extremely interesting biological fluid.
It is the interface between the physiology of an organism and its environment.
In fact, blood is made up of different cells, but the molecule that carries oxygen, the oxygen essential to all living organisms, which is a bit - if I were to take an example related to mechanics - oxygen, is a bit like the fuel that you are going to put in your vehicle.
Without fuel, it's running out of fuel.
And without oxygen, death is assured.
In fact, blood contains a type of cell called red blood cells.
Red blood cells are a small vehicle that will carry gas to the cells of your body.
And to be more precise, this molecule contains a protein called hemoglobin.
Hemoglobin is a molecule that is able to reversibly bind oxygen.
And what was my surprise, to discover that the blood of this marine worm here did not have red blood cells.
Oh, I have to be honest, when I started my discovery, I didn't know the extent of this work.
But [my discovery] went back to the ears of a learned club, called the Red Blood Cell Club.
(Laughter) I was therefore invited to Paris, to a Parisian hospital to present my research work to an audience of doctors, hematologists.
And at the end of my scientific conference, several of them came down from the amphitheater and asked me the following questions: "But sir, you have not found this molecule that has this structure, that has this function?"
"Well, yes!"
"But we have been looking for this molecule for more than 40 years to make it a universal blood substitute!"
You and I have an ABO blood type, Rhesus positive or Rhesus negative.
Only the negative O is of the universal donor type.
The absence of red blood cells in this animal gave this molecule a universal character.
And back in the laboratory, in order to test this hypothesis, I hurried to the beach to collect a few hundred arenicoles, simply to try to collect the hemoglobin contained in their circulatory system, and after purification of this molecule by conventional laboratory techniques, I hurried to transfuse rodents.
And what was my surprise, after exsanguination of these laboratory animals to more than 80%, I transfused this molecule to these animals, and nothing happened.
(Laughter) The organisms, these rodents, lived with seaworm hemoglobin.
An astonishing discovery, and today a huge hope for medicine.
A thumb of the nose to all those skeptics who asked me the question: "But what's the point of studying the breathing of a marine worm?
(Laughter) You really don't have other things to do in a CNRS laboratory? »
(Laughter) In order to support this research work, I am forced to leave the CNRS to create a biotechnology company that will be responsible for developing these molecules for medical applications.
And it only takes a few hundred grams of arenicola to make a globular pouch.
The applications of this molecule are numerous.
What for?
Well, simply because oxygen is at the center of all biological and physiological processes, therefore, ultimately, of life.
The first years of the creation of this company, I spent them developing an industrial process of production of my marine worms.
Indeed, being a biologist, it was out of the question for me to go and defaunal all the beaches in Brittany.
And today, these worms are produced in aquaculture, in a totally controlled and traced environment.
Several hundred tons of this animal are produced in aquaculture.
Apart from the worm, the raw material, the biomass, it was also necessary to find an industrial production system for extracting these molecules under pharmaceutical conditions.
And today, we actually have a whole process that extracts molecules from biomass.
From this industrial process and production of marine worms, the applications are extremely numerous.
And I'm going to give you three, but there are many.
First, it is blood transfusion.
You know, when you donate blood, a blood bag can be kept for 42 days, because red blood cells are perishable.
In addition, the cold chain must be maintained at 4°C.
I remind you that this molecule is not contained in a red blood cell.
And it is thus possible to obtain freeze-dried blood, i.e. powdered blood, which can be dissolved with pharmaceutical water.
So no more storage problem.
No more storage problems at 4°C.
This product could be quickly available in emergency areas, in cataclysm areas, where we really need to transfuse patients.
This product is now in development thanks to a partnership we have with the US army.
The second application is wound healing.
So not just any type of wound.
Wounds that will be found in people who suffer from diabetes, called diabetic foot syndrome, people who suffer from bedsores, severe burns, all these wounds have the characteristic of poorly healing.
What for?
Well, simply because blood circulation hurts.
And unfortunately, the wounds that will be found in people with diabetes usually end badly since most of these people are amputated.
And this affects 20 million people around the world.
We were able to show that dressings impregnated with this molecule were able to deliver oxygen to the feet, therefore to these wounds, and therefore, ultimately, to avoid amputation.
The third of these applications, which is now the most successful since a human trial will take place at the end of the year, is organ transplantation.
In France, 500 people die per year due to lack of grafts on a waiting list of 19,000 patients.
What for?
Because in fact, the solutions we use today in the clinic are composed only of water and salt but no oxygen carrier.
When an organ is removed from a donor, it is immediately disconnected from the bloodstream.
And we were able to show that by using this molecule, it was possible to significantly increase the shelf life of a graft.
A heart today is four hours, between the collection at the donor and the time when it is transplanted to the recipient.
One kidney is 12 hours.
With this molecule, today, we have been able to double the storage time of these organs and multiply by four the storage time of a kidney.
So, today, we are able to increase the pool of grafts available for transplantation.
Research is advancing, but it is not moving as fast as we would like.
What for?
Because the drug cycle is long, very long, very, very long, and while waiting for the market launch of our product, which could save millions of lives around the world, I can only encourage you to go and donate blood.
Be generous to save lives.
And a little advice between friends, go quickly, because tomorrow, it could be a gesture of another time.
Thank you.
