I'm just coming back from Agadez, Niger.
Agadez, perhaps some know, it was the pearl of the Sahara, the gateway to the desert, the blessed stage of the Paris-Dakar.
Today there is not one tourist since the kidnappings of 2010.
On the other hand, there are migrants, hundreds and hundreds of migrants from West Africa.
The mayor told me: during the migration season, the city's population triples.
In 2 weeks when it will be less hot.
(39) instead of 45.
For those crossing the Sahara in the back of pick-up trucks to Libya, it counts.
So you're going to tell me: not yet stories of migrants, we only hear that.
What if I told you that, in fact, we don't talk about it at all.
We are only talking about refugees.
The ones you are shown on TV are Syrians, Iraqis.
They are fleeing a war.
It was explained to us that they are doctors, lawyers, that at home, they have a big house, a housekeeper.
They're kind of like us, they're white.
I cover Africa for Le Point magazine.
And the ones I've started following since June are the ones we don't want at home.
They are poor, not very educated, they are black.
They will never have refugee status.
They will always be confined to that of migrants on the move.
When Syrians take a few weeks to reach Europe, they take several years.
Many remain stuck in Libya.
Some are murdered there for no reason.
Many die on the way to the Sahara.
The desert is littered with corpses.
The idea came to me in April: I was queuing in a service for my computer.
A nice retiree came to sit next to me, looking for company.
She asked me what my job was.
So I told him: reporter in Africa.
She said, "Poor man, it must not be funny."
I said, "No, I like it."
"I don't understand why these people come to us.
There is no job for them.
They come for the allocs?
Then they sleep on my landing and they smell strong. »
So I said, "Madam, I know where they come from and you would do the same."
My ticket number was finally out, I got up, draped in my dignity, and then I asked myself: do we really know why they are leaving, these people?
Those who are not fleeing a war.
Are they really better off with us?
So I looked for a country whose inhabitants would flee en masse and which would not be at war.
It was not very difficult, the International Organization for Migration had just released a report, and the country with the highest number of nationals in absolute terms had attempted to cross the Mediterranean between January and March 2015 was The Gambia.
More than Syria, more than Nigeria.
Nigeria has a population of 175 million.
The Gambia: 1.9.
Very small country.
It was a general save-who-can.
I wanted to understand.
Of course, there were clues: a dictator who arrived in a coup in '94, Yaya Jammeh -- claims that he can cure AIDS with a drink made from plants and verses from the Koran, which makes his opponents disappear, when they are not shot in public.
There were the economic indicators: 1700 dollars of GDP per capita, which places the country 210th out of 230.
Human development.
They are 172nd out of 187.
In short, misery.
Once there, I realized that it was even more complicated.
It's always like that.
We always discover on the spot.
It was a mixture of poverty, ignorance, hope, social pressure that drove young people to leave.
And there was absolutely nothing that could deter them.
That's why I followed the path, I went to Agadez, the migration hub.
And that's why I want to talk to you tonight about everything we think we know about migrants that is absolutely false.
First misconception: it's super expensive to cross; With all this money, they couldn't have done anything else?
Assemble a box?
Well, no.
Because they don't leave with all the money they need for their trip, they don't have it.
They work along the way.
Take the example of Jamal Barry, 25, met in Gambia, near Serekunda.
Djamal manufactures furniture.
When I met him, his last order was a month ago: two armchairs, a 2-seater sofa, a 3-seater sofa.
Paid 450 dalasis by his boss.
9 euros for 12 days of work.
Djamal's parents died, he has 4 brothers and sisters, he wanted to send money from Europe, and then like many, he had to stop in Libya.
He had no money at all.
He had been racketeed at the checkpoint of all the countries crossed.
So, Senegal, Mali, Burkina Faso, Niger, Libya.
And then he was kidnapped.
And then he got sick.
So he came back after 8 months.
He still drew me the truck on which the Tuaregs transport migrants in the Sahara.
You can see, these are cages arranged to store as much as possible.
He was sitting at the end of a beam.
He had to hang on so as not to fall because the truck does not stop.
At the beginning of the journey, they were tight.
And less and less, because they were throwing the bodies of those who were dying of dehydration into the desert.
He told me, "Every day I'm going to go back because I'm already dead here."
Second misconception.
They are disloyal.
They are abandoning their countries that need these vital forces.
It's exactly the opposite: they leave to help the family.
In Africa, there is no pension insurance.
Children ensure their parents' old age.
Take the case of this gentleman, Balamin Jaiteh.
The photo he holds in his hands is that of his son, Yankuba.
Yankuba was 23 years old when he attempted the journey, he too thought he would reach Europe, he too had to stop in Sebha, Libya.
And he was unlucky.
Libyans were looking for an African from his ghetto.
These are the houses where migrants pile up before they can continue.
He told them he didn't know where he was.
He was told, "You black people all know each other."
They doused him with gasoline.
They scratched a match.
Yankuba burned to death.
His father took days to talk to me, he felt guilty.
He said, "I did that too, as early as 1975.
I have worked in Mali, Burkina Faso, Gabon, Ivory Coast, Niger and Libya.
It's normal to help his old parents, besides all the time he could work, he sent us money; You see, we were able to redo the house. »
His wife was staring at the ground.
One of his daughters had gone into hiding to cry.
When I asked Balamin, "You forbade your sons to leave?
You told them it was dangerous?
He said, "No, not clearly. »
For the moment, it is not a source of money that he can deprive himself of.
Third misconception.
They are not so poor, they have cell phones.
So, yes, they have cell phones, sometimes they even have just that.
No electricity, no running water but smartphones.
Not state-of-the-art, old imitations that take hours to reload, hours to display a web page.
Because the most fearsome, the most lying smuggler is not the little hunger pan of Agadez who crams migrants in the back of his pick-up.
No, it's the internet.
It's social networks.
They spend hours dreaming in front of the photos of those who have already passed through Europe, and dreaming that one day too, they will manage to cross.
Fourth misconception.
They will all sweep the France to pick up family allowances.
No, it's borderline offensive, I know, but not one talked about France.
At the bus station in Niamey, the capital of Niger, I spoke with a Malian who insisted on speaking to me in English, because his boss was from Nigeria, so English-speaking, he wanted to practice his English.
It was aimed at Europe, but not at all at France.
England or especially Germany.
Even the Senegalese in the ghettos of Agadez, they dream of Germany, they do not even know that French is not spoken there.
As for allowances, no one knows that it exists.
